# Investment Committee Memo

## 1. Executive Summary  
Limoneira Co. (NASDAQ: LMNR) is an integrated agribusiness and real-estate platform with diversified cash flows from citrus, avocados, specialty crops, packing/distribution, land development and water-rights monetization.  Management targets mid-single-digit revenue growth, stable to modest margin expansion and net leverage sub-3× EBITDA (currently ~2.5×).  Key strengths include first-lien security on domestic assets, an undrawn revolver and a de-risked real-estate pipeline.  Primary concerns center on weather and commodity-price cyclicality, input-cost inflation, interest-rate rises and covenant-lite documentation.  We recommend WATCHLIST: proceed with further diligence on covenant mechanics, EBITDA add-backs and springing maintenance tests before committing.

## 2. Sponsor, Transaction and Use of Proceeds  
• Borrower: Limoneira Co., a longstanding public agribusiness/land-developer.  
• Proposed Debt: Incremental first-lien Term Loan B and revolver tranche (pari passu) to refinance maturing paper, fund working capital seasonality and support select CapEx (packhouse improvements, water infrastructure).  
• Use of Proceeds:  
  - Redemption/refinancing of existing secured debt  
  - Seasonal working-capital drawdowns during planting/harvest peaks  
  - Ongoing growth CapEx (~$15 M annually)  
  - Optional strategic real-estate JV contributions  

## 3. Business Model, Revenue Diversification and Market Context  
• Core Agriculture: lemons, oranges, avocados, specialty crops sold under long-term offtakes and spot; exposed to weather, labor and commodity prices.  
• Packing & Distribution: in-house processing for Limoneira plus fee income from third-party growers; margin linked to throughput volumes.  
• Real-Estate Development: residential/commercial projects on ~30,000 acres with de-risked entitlements; countercyclical but sensitive to interest rates and permitting timelines.  
• Water Resources: ownership of water rights and storage infrastructure that underwrites crop reliability and generates occasional sales.  
• Market Context: high barriers to entry in land/water-rights, ESG and regulatory pressures on water use, input-cost inflation and interest-rate impacts on housing demand.

## 4. Historical Financial Performance and Credit Metrics  
• Revenue Growth: mid-single digits y/y, driven by stable crop volumes and lumpy real-estate cash-ins.  
• EBITDA Margins: relatively stable ~15–18%, with slight upside from packhouse efficiency and cost management.  
• Cash Flow Profile: seasonal WC outflows during planting/harvest; intermittent spikes from land-sale closings and water monetization.  
• Leverage and Coverage: Net Debt/EBITDA ~2.5× (moderate band), with healthy interest coverage today.  Undrawn revolver and minimal maturities in the next 12 months mitigate near-term refinance risk.  
• Scenario Sensitivities:  
  – Downside: adverse weather + cost inflation + weak prices → flat/negative revenue, margin compression, free cash-flow erosion, leverage drifting toward 3.0×.  
  – Upside: strong yields + pricing + real-estate/water monetization → leverage falling below 2.0× and expanded coverage cushions.

## 5. Structure, Documentation and Covenants  
• Security: first-lien on US real estate, inventory, receivables; broad US-subsidiary guarantees; borrowing-base mechanics at 80–85% AR.  
• Covenant Profile: appears covenant-lite with incurrence only tests (leverage and interest coverage for new debt/dividends); no standing maintenance covenants or minimum-liquidity tests.  
• Documentation Strengths: seniority, broad collateral package, negative-pledge and cross-default protections.  
• Documentation Gaps / Open Questions:  
  - Definition of EBITDA and permissible add-backs for incurrence tests  
  - Presence and triggers for any springing maintenance covenants (e.g., interest coverage floor if availability <25%)  
  - Scope and thresholds for restricted-payments/investment baskets  
  - Intercreditor terms vis-à-vis unsecured notes  

## 6. Downside Protection and Loss Pathways  
• Security Package: first-lien collateral and receivables financing limit unsecured lender loss given default.  
• Covenant Enhancements: negotiate springing maintenance triggers, tighter add-back baskets and restricted-payment caps to curtail over-distribution.  
• Structural Protections: seasonal borrowing-base revolver, accelerated amortization tied to leverage breaches (e.g., >3.0× net debt/EBITDA), equity cure rights.  
• Loss Pathway: if cost pass-through fades under fixed offtakes and interest rates rise, EBITDA contracts while interest expense climbs, free cash flow turns negative, revolver usage spikes and leverage breaches incurrence caps—with limited ongoing covenant visibility.

## 7. Key Risks and Mitigants  
1. Weather/Climate Variability  
   • Mitigant: crop diversification, insurance programs, geographic spread.  
2. Input-Cost Inflation & Cost Pass-Through  
   • Mitigant: packhouse efficiency investments, spot-market exposure, price-floor collars in offtake agreements.  
3. Commodity Price Cyclicality & Export Risk  
   • Mitigant: long-term retail partnerships, diversified channels, pricing collars.  
4. Rising Interest Rates  
   • Mitigant: minimal near-term maturities, undrawn revolver, potential to hedge floating exposures.  
5. Real-Estate Execution  
   • Mitigant: focus on de-risked parcels, JV structures sharing development cost/risk.  
6. Documentation Gaps  
   • Mitigant: further diligence on EBITDA add-backs, tack on springing covenants, tighten restricted-payment baskets.
